','Usually','Always','Emma has made the adjustment to being a student in IB History at ICS seamlessly. She regularly participates and has begun to work up to the standards required in my class. I am writing this report to both congratulate her on her transition, but also to highlight my concern that she will need to keep up the hard work in order to meet the writing expectations for my class. From our conversations, Emma has told me that she did not write as frequently in her previous school. Her grade was very low until this past week when she elected to do a rewrite of an essay, and scored very well. Her first attempt was a 3 out of 7, in part, because Emma froze and then threw away a page of writing. I hope she has worked that fear out of her system and is ready to use the rest of this quarter as a chance to catch up to her peers and start to perform consistently at the level of a 5/6 out of 7.  I know Emma can do this because she was able to write at that level on her rewrite. She is free to speak to me at any time to talk about her writing and her understanding in history class. ','2012-02-22 08:24:29','2012-02-22 08:24:29'),(450,1706,6,NULL,'Q3','Unacceptable','Unacceptable','Unacceptable','Always','Ammanuel is a polite, cheerful member of the 8th grade World Cultures class but is struggling to submit work and to remain on task in class.  He has not handed in any of his work for his Age of Exploration and Conquest unit (graphic organizer on artifacts; notes on explorers from in class reading; and monument from different perspectives) despite several reminders and assurances he would hand this work in.  All of these assignments were worked on during class time - not for homework.  Ammanuel was also unable to work effectively with his partner during this unit; nor is he using his laptop to submit work in this class.  I strongly suggest a parent meeting in the near future to work out ways we can help Ammanuel develop the study and organizational skills he needs if he is to progress to 9th grade in this subject.','2012-02-22 11:44:51','2012-02-22 11:44:51'),(451,3864,5,NULL,'Q3','Occasionally','Always','Occasionally','Usually','Ammanual is a polite and respectful student in my class. He is adjusting to a new school in the middle of the year and doing so without much trouble. Unfortunately, he has not been able to write at the level demanded in my class. His first complete essay was a 3 out of 7. After receiving feedback, he had the opportunity to rewrite this essay on one of two days after school and he chose not to do so. Writing is a major component of IB History and it is a primary means of assessment in the class. We will be writing an essay every four to five blocks for the rest of the year. It is very important that Ammanual learn how to write in the manner that the IB demands. In order to help the entire class, I have students write on a prompt for the first 10 minutes of every class. I do not grade this writing, but it does form the basis for discussion for the class. Ammanual has not posted his writing attempts to the course website for the past four classes and I will speak to him about what he is writing during this time. I do see him working on his laptop and have read entries over his shoulder, but he does not produce more than a sentence or two in 10 minutes of writing.  For Ammanual to perform better in History, I suggest that he take the start of class writing more seriously. Another way Ammanual can improve his writing is to spend 5-10 minutes at the end of each night\'s assignment and write a summary statement. This statement can help Ammanual consolidate his knowledge and provide more practice. He is free to speak to me at any time to talk about his writing and his understanding in history class.\r\n','2012-03-05 11:58:49','2012-03-05 11:58:49'),(452,1412,1,NULL,'Q3','Usually','Usually','Unacceptable','Always','Adam is demonstrating understanding in all benchmarks, and is clearly progressing towards exceed