rning focused on understanding safety issues and the human body.  Students learned how to identify various parts of the human body as well as how to protect themselves from injuries. The students will use this knowledge to take care of themselves and others.  Students were pre-assessed on producing posters, presentations and on the research process.\r\nFor Quarter 4 students will learn about tobacco, alcohol and drug prevention as well as sexual education and a healthy lifestyle.\r\n','2012-03-23 14:09:48','2012-03-26 11:51:02'),(46,93,5,'Q3','\r\nIn Science 6, during Quarter 3, students explored reading and interpreting area and topographical maps, in particular, the region of Bahir Dar where we went for our class trip.   Following that,  for the remainder of quarter 3, instruction and learning outcomes were focused on experimental design and formal report writing.  During this process students had to create their own experiment, state a question which they were to explore, identify the different variables (independent, dependent and controlled) of their experiment, as well as write a clear procedure, collect and organize raw data, analyze that data and make a conclusion based on the data they collected.  Students received feedback on their first experiment and will continue to work on all these aspects of experimental design in Quarter 4 with a second experiment assignment.  In addition, quarter 4 will also include a project in which students design objects that act like submarines to extend their understanding of buoyancy concepts.   \r\n\r\nDetails of grades and comments on assessments can be found on the e-learning site.  Science 6 SEM 2 -login using your child\'s username and password, then go to SETTINGS section and press \'grades\' button.  \r\n\r\nPlease let me know if you have any questions or comments.  Ms. Ashby','2012-03-23 17:37:27','2012-03-23 17:37:27'),(47,95,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 7 Science we completed our units â€œPlants and Lightâ€ and â€œHeat, Energy, and Sunlightâ€ and began the units â€œProductivity in Ecosystemsâ€ and â€œEnergy Storage.â€  \r\n\r\nIn the â€œHeat, Energy, and Sunlightâ€ unit we continued to build our understanding of heat and light in order to answer the question â€œHow much heat is produced by one square centimeter of sunlight striking the Earth\'s surface in one minute?â€.  In groups, the students built a device to capture sunlight and measure it as heat.  They summarized their results in a formal lab report and took a quiz on the process.  \r\n\r\nIn the â€œProductivity in Ecosystemsâ€ unit we gathered plant and animal biomass to investigate the production of compost.  We have also begun setting up our farm plots to answer the question, â€œHow much edible biomass can be produced in one square meter of land?â€.  In groups, the students are responsible for the set-up and maintenance of their farm plots with little teacher assistance.  \r\n\r\nOn the horizon are our units on â€œA Search for Evidenceâ€, â€œThe Literature of Chemistryâ€, and â€œAnalysis and Synthesis of Compounds,â€ all introducing students to basic chemistry.  We will also be exploring the units â€œChemical Transformations,â€ â€œRespiration and the Consumer Model,â€ and â€œBioenergetics,â€ which discuss photosynthesis, respiration, and the relationship between both, respectively.  \r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:16:14','2012-03-23 18:16:14'),(48,96,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 7 Science we completed our units â€œPlants and Lightâ€ and â€œHeat, Energy, and Sunlightâ€ and began the units â€œProductivity in Ecosystemsâ€ and â€œEnergy Storage.â€  \r\n\r\nIn the â€œHeat, Energy, and Sunlightâ€ unit we continued to build our understanding of heat and light in order to answer the question â€œHow much heat is produced by one square centimeter of sunlight striking the Earth\'s surface in one minute?â€.  In groups, the students built a device to capture sunlight and measure it as heat.  They summarized their results in a formal lab report and took a quiz on the process.  \r\n\r\nIn the â€œProductivity in Ecosystemsâ€ unit we gathered plant and animal biomass to investigate the production of compost.  We have also begun setting up our farm plots to answer the question, â€œHow much edible biomass can be produced in one square meter of land?â€.  In groups, the students are responsible for the set-up and maintenance of their farm plots with little teacher assistance.  \r\n\r\nOn the horizon are our units on â€œA Search for Evidenceâ€, â€œThe Literature of Chemistryâ€, and â€œAnalysis and Synthesis of Compounds,â€ all introducing students to basic chemistry.  We will also be exploring the units â€œChemical Transformations,â€ â€œRespiration and the Consumer Model,â€ and â€œBioenergetics,â€ which discuss photosynthesis, respiration, and the relationship between both, respectively.  \r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:16:31','2012-03-23 18:16:31'),(49,221,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 7 Health we investigated the units â€œThe Environment and Your Healthâ€ and â€œChemicals, the Environment, and Youâ€, and have begun the unit â€œDrugs: Investigations into Biology and Behavior.â€  The first two units introduced students to the study of how the environment impacts human health by researching and exploring topics as health scientists.  The students conducted a study on the effect of a chemical of their choice on a model organism, radish seeds.  The students wrote up their finding in a formal lab report.   \r\n\r\nOur current unit is focusing on alcohol and its effect on living things.  Throughout all topics we are using science to investigate human health.  We will continue the â€œDrugsâ€ unit into Quarter 4 and begin a unit on nutrition.  If there\'s time, we\'ll explore our brains.  Fun!  \r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:17:01','2012-03-23 18:17:01'),(50,218,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 7 Health we investigated the units â€œThe Environment and Your Healthâ€ and â€œChemicals, the Environment, and Youâ€, and have begun the unit â€œDrugs: Investigations into Biology and Behavior.â€  The first two units introduced students to the study of how the environment impacts human health by researching and exploring topics as health scientists.  The students conducted a study on the effect of a chemical of their choice on a model organism, radish seeds.  The students wrote up their finding in a formal lab report.   \r\n\r\nOur current unit is focusing on alcohol and its effect on living things.  Throughout all topics we are using science to investigate human health.  We will continue the â€œDrugsâ€ unit into Quarter 4 and begin a unit on nutrition.  If there\'s time, we\'ll explore our brains.  Fun!  \r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:17:50','2012-03-23 18:17:50'),(51,225,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 8 Health we have investigated the units â€œFamily Healthâ€ and â€œThe Science of Healthy Behaviors.â€  This introduced our understanding of why people behave the way they do.  \r\n\r\nOur current unit â€œSex and Sexualityâ€ investigates how sexual behavior influences human health.  Students have been conducting research on safe sex practices with an emphasis on abstinence.  We have also researched and reported on the dangers posed by sexually transmitted diseases.  \r\n\r\nIn Quarter 4 will will continue our present unit and discuss how media influences body image.  We will also be exploring cancer, a topic I feel is immensely important.\r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:18:23','2012-03-23 18:18:23'),(52,224,14,'Q3','Hello Parents/Guardians,\r\n\r\nIn Quarter 3 of Grade 8 Health we have investigated the units â€œFamily Healthâ€ and â€œThe Science of Healthy Behaviors.â€  This introduced our understanding of why people behave the way they do.  \r\n\r\nOur current unit â€œSex and Sexualityâ€ investigates how sexual behavior influences human health.  Students have been conducting research on safe sex practices with an emphasis on abstinence.  We have also researched and reported on the dangers posed by sexually transmitted diseases.  \r\n\r\nIn Quarter 4 will will continue our present unit and discuss how media influences body image.  We will also be exploring cancer, a topic I feel is immensely important.\r\n\r\nEamonn Walsh','2012-03-23 18:18:27','2012-03-23 18:18:27'),(53,61,5,'Q3','In Math 6, during Quarter 3, students worked on algorithms for addition, subtraction and multiplication of fraction and mixed numbers.  Conversions of fractions to equivalent fractions, mixed numbers, decimals, percents (and vise versa) were also practiced.  Students estimated and evaluated percent of a number as well as creating percent circle graphs from tables of data.  We are currently in the midst of creating, evaluating and graphing algebraic expression, examining positive and negative numbers,  and reviewing concepts such as greatest common factor (GCF) and lowest common multiple (LCM).  During Quarter 4 we will explore topics in Geometry such as drawing, measuring and classifying angles, using a coordinate grid to plot points, translate, flip and rotate images, as well as using properties  of  angles, triangles, parallelograms, and transversals.  Problem solving strategies will be emphasized as students will be challenged to apply all their learning to solve open-ended word problem type questions. \r\n\r\nDetailed information about specific benchmark grades and homework completion is available on the e-learning site under Math 6 SEM 2.  Ask your child to log-in and show you their \'grades\' (button is under the SETTINGS sidebar heading).  \r\n\r\nAny questions or comments, please don\'t hesitate to email or call.  \r\nSincerely, Ms. Ashby','2012-03-23 19:56:41','2012-03-23 19:56:41'),(54,63,5,'Q3','In Math 6, during Quarter 3, students worked on algorithms for addition, subtraction and multiplication of fraction and mixed numbers.  Conversions of fractions to equivalent fractions, mixed numbers, decimals, percents (and vise versa) were also practiced.  Students estimated and evaluated percent of a number as well as creating percent circle graphs from tables of data.  We are currently in the midst of creating, evaluating and graphing algebraic expression, examining positive and negative numbers,  and reviewing concepts such as greatest common factor (GCF) and lowest common multiple (LCM).  During Quarter 4 we will explore topics in Geometry such as drawing, measuring and classifying angles, using a coordinate grid to plot points, translate, flip and rotate images, as well as using properties  of  angles, triangles, parallelograms, and transversals.  Problem solving strategies will be emphasized as students will be challenged to apply all their learning to solve open-ended word problem type questions. \r\n\r\nDetailed information about specific benchmark grades and homework completion is available on the e-learing site under Math 6 SEM 2.  Ask your child to log-in and show you their \'grades\' (button is under the SETTINGS sidebar heading).  \r\n\r\nAny questions or comments, please don\'t hesitate to email or call.  \r\nSincerely, Ms. Ashby','2012-03-23 19:57:03','2012-03-23 19:57:03'),(55,38,7,'Q3','In 6th grade English Language Arts during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on reading and writing informational texts.  Students have practiced elements of report writing such as, locating appropriate information, writing an informational paragraph, and analyzing the pros and cons of various text structures within an informational text. We have recently begun to evaluate sources based on their credibility. They will use this knowledge to help guide, inform, and organize their own writing of nonfiction. Vocabulary, grammar, and independent reading studies continued and are ongoing components of instruction. \r\n\r\nAdditional Benchmarks to be assessed in quarter 4:\r\nâ€¢ Determine a theme or central idea of a text and how it is conveyed through particular details.\r\nâ€¢ Introduce a topic; organize ideas, concepts, and information, using strategies such as definition, classification, comparison/contrast, and cause/effect; include formatting (e.g., headings), graphics (e.g., charts, tables), and multimedia when useful to aiding comprehension.\r\nâ€¢ Develop the topic with relevant facts, definitions, concrete details, quotations, or other information and examples.\r\nâ€¢ Use appropriate transitions to clarify the relationships among ideas and concepts.\r\nâ€¢ Gather relevant information from multiple print and digital sources; assess the credibility of each source; and quote or paraphrase the data and conclusions of others while avoiding plagiarism and providing basic bibliographic information for sources.\r\nâ€¢ Engage effectively in a range of collaborative discussions (one-on-one, in groups, and teacher- led) with diverse partners on grade 6 topics, texts, and issues, building on othersâ€™ ideas and expressing their own clearly.','2012-03-25 07:14:35','2012-03-25 07:18:02'),(56,39,7,'Q3','In 6th grade English Language Arts during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on reading and writing informational texts.  Students have practiced elements of report writing such as, locating appropriate information, writing an informational paragraph, and analyzing the pros and cons of various text structures within an informational text. We have recently begun to evaluate sources based on their credibility. They will use this knowledge to help guide, inform, and organize their own writing of nonfiction. Vocabulary, grammar, and independent reading studies continued and are ongoing components of instruction. \r\n\r\nAdditional Benchmarks to be assessed in quarter 4:\r\nâ€¢ Determine a theme or central idea of a text and how it is conveyed through particular details.\r\nâ€¢ Introduce a topic; organize ideas, concepts, and information, using strategies such as definition, classification, comparison/contrast, and cause/effect; include formatting (e.g., headings), graphics (e.g., charts, tables), and multimedia when useful to aiding comprehension.\r\nâ€¢ Develop the topic with relevant facts, definitions, concrete details, quotations, or other information and examples.\r\nâ€¢ Use appropriate transitions to clarify the relationships among ideas and concepts.\r\nâ€¢ Gather relevant information from multiple print and digital sources; assess the credibility of each source; and quote or paraphrase the data and conclusions of others while avoiding plagiarism and providing basic bibliographic information for sources.\r\nâ€¢ Engage effectively in a range of collaborative discussions (one-on-one, in groups, and teacher- led) with diverse partners on grade 6 topics, texts, and issues, building on othersâ€™ ideas and expressing their own clearly.','2012-03-25 07:15:20','2012-03-25 07:15:20'),(57,130,7,'Q3','During the first half of the semester sixth grade Social Studies focused on how changes in political and economic systems impact individuals and groups as well as, how individuals or groups influence behavior, perceptions or a course of events. We practiced these concepts through the context of the ancient Greeks. In particular, we discussed the influence of geography on lifestyle, the rise of democracy, and compared life in Athens with that of Sparta. We have recently begun to close the Greek unit with a more analytical look at the topics covered thus far. Shortly after the break we will begin a unit on the ancient Romans.\r\n\r\nAdditional Benchmarks to be assessed in quarter 4:\r\n\r\nâ€¢ Describe conflict between cultures\r\nâ€¢ Describe the historical development of social, political and cultural groups\r\nâ€¢ Identify and explain components in an individual\'s belief system','2012-03-25 07:17:00','2012-03-25 07:17:00'),(58,129,7,'Q3','During the first half of the semester sixth grade Social Studies focused on how changes in political and economic systems impact individuals and groups as well as, how individuals or groups influence behavior, perceptions or a course of events. We practiced these concepts through the context of the ancient Greeks. In particular, we discussed the influence of geography on lifestyle, the rise of democracy, and compared life in Athens with that of Sparta. We have recently begun to close the Greek unit with a more analytical look at the topics covered thus far. Shortly after the break we will begin a unit on the ancient Romans.\r\n\r\nAdditional Benchmarks to be assessed in quarter 4:\r\n\r\nâ€¢ Describe conflict between cultures\r\nâ€¢ Describe the historical development of social, political and cultural groups\r\nâ€¢ Identify and explain components in an individual\'s belief system','2012-03-25 07:17:07','2012-03-25 07:17:07'),(59,231,7,'Q3','During the fist half of the semester Media Studies mainly focused on the use of a graphic design editing software called GIMP. In addition, some basic journalism, photography, and graphic design concepts were covered as well. Students completed practice exercises such as, identifying the parts of a news story, taking photos based on a specific skill, and manipulating text and photos using GIMP. The second half of the semester will require students to apply these basic skills in order to create content for the Middle School Website. \r\n\r\nAdditional Benchmark to be assessed in quarter 4:\r\n\r\nâ€¢ Create an original news story about a topic of personal interest and document a reflection on the quality of the production.\r\n','2012-03-25 07:29:41','2012-03-25 07:29:41'),(60,132,33,'Q3','In Social Studies during quarter 3 we moved from an examination of Asian medieval cultures to examining the culture of medieval Europe. During this time students also completed a unit on Ethiopian culture centred around the field trip to Arba Minch. Students continue to evaluate cultures through the lens of religion, technology, government and social structure. As well, the course contains elements of geography and resource studies.','2012-03-25 15:01:37','2012-03-25 15:01:37'),(61,133,33,'Q3','In Social Studies during quarter 3 we moved from an examination of Asian medieval cultures to examining the culture of medieval Europe. During this time students also completed a unit on Ethiopian culture centred around the field trip to Arba Minch. Students continue to evaluate cultures through the lens of religion, technology, government and social structure. As well, the course contains elements of geography and resource studies.','2012-03-25 15:01:45','2012-03-25 15:01:45'),(62,128,33,'Q3','Origins of Knowledge is a class that delves into the philosophy and sociology of different cultures. OK examines how an individual develops a belief system and the different factors in this process.','2012-03-25 15:34:01','2012-03-25 15:34:01'),(63,131,33,'Q3','In Social Studies during quarter 3 we moved from an examination of ancient middle eastern cultures to examining the culture of ancient Greece. Students continue to evaluate cultures through the lens of religion, technology, government and social structure. As well, the course contains elements of geography and resource studies.','2012-03-25 16:33:29','2012-03-25 16:33:29'),(64,186,33,'Q3','Survey of Music delves into musical concepts such as tone, melody, harmony, rhythm and beat. We also investigate historical eras to give students an understanding of the historical roots of modern popular music.','2012-03-25 16:44:15','2012-03-25 16:44:15'),(65,65,28,'Q3','Pre Algebra\r\nThe topics we have studied in Pre-Algebra this quarter are:  Exponents and scientific notation; Fractions and solving rational equations; Ratios, rates and proportions; Probability; and Algebraic patterns.  We have just begun to study Trigonometry.  A major topic next quarter will be Linear functions and graphs. ','2012-03-26 05:58:10','2012-03-26 06:00:25'),(66,67,28,'Q3','Pre Algebra\r\nThe topics we have studied in Pre-Algebra this quarter are:  Exponents and scientific notation; Fractions and solving rational equations; Ratios, rates and proportions; Probability; and Algebraic patterns.  We have just begun to study Trigonometry.  A major topic next quarter will be Linear functions and graphs. ','2012-03-26 05:59:54','2012-03-26 06:00:14'),(67,64,28,'Q3','Maths 7\r\nThe topics we have studied in Maths 7 this quarter are:  Fractions; Integers; Coordinates; Simplifying algebraic expressions; Solving Equations. Next quarter, we will look at Linear functions, Ratios and Proportions; Perimeter and Area of shapes; Percentages; and Probability. ','2012-03-26 06:01:08','2012-03-26 06:01:08'),(68,43,6,'Q3','In 8th grade English Language Arts during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on reading and writing arguments and editorials as well as comparing and contrasting books and films.  Students focused their reading of arguments on analyzing and evaluating the relevancy and sufficiency of claimsâ€”in essence determining the validity and effectiveness of an argument. Students applied this knowledge to writing their own arguments by assuming a position on the superiority of either the book or film version of novels read in class.  Class debates, forthcoming, will allow students to demonstrate their listening and speaking skills also around the theme of argument.   Vocabulary, grammar, and independent reading studies continued and are ongoing components of instruction. ','2012-03-26 06:08:04','2012-03-26 06:08:04'),(69,314,11,'Q3','In this section of EAL 2, Karen is working on homework and individual assignments.  She starts the class by checking her email and moodle sites and transfers any homework into her planner.  We then review what she will focus on for the day and I assist her as needed.  \r\n','2012-03-27 05:35:13','2012-03-27 05:35:13'),(70,12,11,'Q3','In EAL 1 this quarter, we were focused on different reading strategies.  Students learned how to incorporate math into stories, participate in book club discussions, and read within the text, all of which will support them in their general Language Arts classes.  Students were assessed on their participation in the activities, as our class is a place to practice behaviors and language beneficial for their content area courses.  ','2012-03-27 05:35:46','2012-03-27 05:35:46'),(71,5,11,'Q3','In EAL 2 this quarter, we have continued our study of different purposes for writing.  Students have learned writing to express/reflect and to inquire/explore.  For each purpose to writing, students develop a variety of writing prompts and then take one through all of the steps in the writing process.  ','2012-03-27 05:37:49','2012-03-27 05:37:49'),(72,283,11,'Q3','In 6th grade Reading Enrichment class during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on the purpose for reading and writing, poetry, and fairy tales.  Students learned how to annotate a poem to find the theme and tone and how the point-of-view or perspective changes a fairy tale.  They used this information to create final projects where they analyzed a poem and created an original fairy tale.  ','2012-03-27 05:40:31','2012-03-27 05:40:31'),(73,237,35,'Q3','In C block Academic Resource during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on achieving independent academic goals, as stated in their Individual Learning Plans as well as on academic writing. Students learned how to summarize and paraphrase articles and use the information as support for their opinions in persuasive, opinion, and argumentative essays and paragraphs.  They will continue to use these skills as they work on writing structurally coherent and well-organized academic essays and paragraphs in their resource class as well as in their content area courses. Writing fluency, grammar, reading, study skills and problem solving are also ongoing components of instruction. \r\n','2012-03-27 05:59:27','2012-03-27 05:59:27'),(74,239,35,'Q3','In D block Academic Resource during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on achieving independent academic reading goals, as stated in their Individual Learning Plans.  Students focused specifically on their reading goals including:  analyzing word parts (prefixes and suffixes), using context clues to find meaning, using reading comprehension strategy skills, and word attack strategies.  They will use this knowledge as they continue to work toward gains in reading comprehension and fluency both in their resource class and in their content area courses. Writing fluency, grammar, study skills and problem solving are also ongoing components of instruction. ','2012-03-27 06:01:49','2012-03-27 06:01:49'),(75,282,35,'Q3','In 6th grade Reading Enrichment during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on reading fairy tales and poetry.  Students learned the elements of fairy tales. They used this knowledge to write their own creative fairy tales and present them to the class.  Students have also worked on analyzing poetry for its theme, tone, and mood.  Creative writing and independent reading studies continued and are ongoing components of instruction. \r\n','2012-03-27 06:03:19','2012-03-27 06:03:19'),(76,282,35,'Q3','In 6th grade Reading Enrichment during Quarter 3, instruction and learning focused on reading fairy tales and poetry.  Students learned the elements of fairy tales. They used this knowledge to write their own creative fairy tales and present them to the class.  Students have also worked on analyzing poetry for its theme, tone, and mood.  Creative writing and independent reading studies continued and are ongoing components of instruction. \r\n','2012-03-27 06:03:25','2012-03-27 06:03:25'),(77,89,18,'Q3','In Culinary Arts this quarter students learned to describe the function of basic kitchen equipments and appliances, performed a variety of basic cooking procedures, defined a variety of cooking terms, and learned how to cook different types of cookies, breads and pastries.\r\n','2012-03-28 05:31:08','2012-03-28 05:31:08'),(78,90,18,'Q3','In Culinary Arts this quarter students learned to describe the function of basic kitchen equipments and appliances, performed a variety of basic cooking procedures, defined a variety of cooking terms, and learned how to cook different types of cookies, breads and pastries.\r\n','2012-03-28 05:31:19','2012-03-28 05:31:19');
